EasyOverrider

Class ParamListBuilder<O>

  • java.lang.Object
    • EasyOverrider.ParamListBuilder<O>
  • Type Parameters:
    O - the type you're creating the ParamList for

    public class ParamListBuilder<O>
extends Object
    Class to help with building the building of a ParamList.
    Since the ParamList and ParamDescription objects are pretty complicated, this class helps create them in a nice, fluent way.
     

 private static ParamList<Foo> paramList =
                 ParamList.forClass(Foo.class)
                          .withPrimaryParam("id", Foo::getId, Integer.class)
                          .withParam("name", Foo::getName, String.class)
                          .withParam("bar", Foo::getBar, Bar.class)
                          .andThatsIt();

      • forClass

        public static <C> ParamListBuilder<C> forClass(Class<C> parentClass)
        Kicks off a ParamListBuilder for the provided class.
        This is usually done using ParamList.forClass(Class), so that you don't have to import ParamListBuilder. This one is mainly here for ease of use in case there's some confusion between a ParamListBuilder and a ParamList. This way you can call forClass on either with the same results.
        Type Parameters:
        C - the class you're building the parameter list for
        Parameters:
        parentClass - the class you're building the parameter list for
        Returns:
        A ParamListBuilder for the specified class.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the provided class is null.

        Add a new ParamDescriptionSingle to the list with the provided parameters.
        Uses the default ParamMethodRestriction of ParamUsage.INCLUDED_IN_ALL.
        Type Parameters:
        P - the type of the parameter being described
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the parameter, e.g. "id" - cannot be null
        getter - the getter for the parameter, e.g. Product::getId - cannot be null
        paramClass - the class of the parameter in question - cannot be null
        Returns:
        The current ParamListBuilder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if a ParamDescription with the same name has already been added to this builder.
        IllegalArgumentException - if any parameter is null.

      • withPrimaryParam

        public <P> ParamListBuilder<O> withPrimaryParam(String name,
                                                Function<? super O,P> getter,
                                                Class<P> paramClass)
        Add a new ParamDescriptionSingle that represents a primary parameter.
        The default ParamMethodRestriction is ParamUsage.TOSTRING_ONLY.
        The main purpose of a "Primary Parameter" is that it is still included in the toString output of the containing object, even if a recursive toString is detected. The idea is that, if the full contents of the containing object are included elsewhere in the string, this parameter can be used to identify that entry.
        Caution:
        Primary Parameters should be used sparingly as they bypass recursion prevention. Usually these are identifier parameters with simple types such as int or String.
        Type Parameters:
        P - the type of the parameter being described
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the parameter, e.g. "id" - cannot be null
        getter - the getter for the parameter, e.g. Product::getId - cannot be null
        paramClass - the class of the parameter in question - cannot be null
        Returns:
        The current ParamListBuilder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if a ParamDescription with the same name has already been added to this builder.
        IllegalArgumentException - if any parameter is null.
        See Also:
        withPrimaryParam(String, Function, ParamUsage, Class), withParam(String, Function, Class), withCollection(String, Function, Class, Class), withMap(String, Function, Class, Class, Class), withUpdatedPrimaryParam(String, Function, Class), withoutParam(String)

        Add a new ParamDescriptionSingle that represents a primary parameter.
        The main purpose of a "Primary Parameter" is that it is still included in the toString output of the containing object, even if a recursive toString is detected. The idea is that, if the full contents of the containing object are included elsewhere in the string, this parameter can be used to identify that entry.
        Caution 1:
        Primary Parameters should be used sparingly as they bypass recursion prevention. Usually these are identifier parameters with simple types such as int or String.
        Caution 2:
        It is usually unwise to include the primary key column(s) of database entities in equals() and hashCode(). This is because saving the entity can alter the parameter, causing strange inequalities and changing hashCodes.
        Type Parameters:

        Parameters:

        getter - the getter for the parameter, e.g. Product::getId - cannot be null

        public <P> ParamListBuilder<O> withUpdatedParam(String name,
                                                Function<? super O,P> getter,

        Updates the parameter having the provided name with the new values given.
        Uses the default ParamMethodRestriction of ParamUsage.INCLUDED_IN_ALL.

        paramClass - the class of the parameter in question - cannot be null
        Returns:
        The current ParamListBuilder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the provided name is not already defined.
        IllegalArgumentException - if any parameter is null.
        See Also:
        withUpdatedParam(String, Function, ParamUsage, Class), withUpdatedPrimaryParam(String, Function, Class), withUpdatedCollection(String, Function, Class, Class), withUpdatedMap(String, Function, Class, Class, Class), withParam(String, Function, Class), withoutParam(String)

      • withUpdatedCollection

        public <E,P extends Collection> ParamListBuilder<O> withUpdatedCollection(String name,
                                                                          Function<? super O,P> getter,
                                                                          ParamUsage paramMethodRestriction,
                                                                          Class<P> paramClass,
                                                                          Class<E> entryClass)
        Updates the parameter having the provided name to be a collection with the new values given.
        Specifically, a new ParamDescriptionCollection is created using the given info. Then the old ParamDescription is replaced with this new one.
        Type Parameters:
        P - the type of the parameter (must be a Collection of some sort)
        E - the type of the entries in the parameter
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the parameter, e.g. "id" - cannot be null
        getter - the getter for the parameter, e.g. Product::getId - cannot be null
        paramMethodRestriction - the ParamUsage value indicating how this parameter should be used - cannot be null
        paramClass - the class of the parameter in question - cannot be null
        entryClass - the class of the entries in the parameter - cannot be null
        Returns:
        The current ParamListBuilder.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the provided name is not already defined.
        IllegalArgumentException - if any parameter is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if the ParamMethodRestrictionRestriction doesn't allow the provided ParamUsage.
        See Also:
        withUpdatedCollection(String, Function, Class, Class), withUpdatedParam(String, Function, ParamUsage, Class), withUpdatedMap(String, Function, ParamUsage, Class, Class, Class), withCollection(String, Function, ParamUsage, Class, Class), withoutParam(String)
